{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The content passed to the summary-generation step includes data retrieved from all three sources.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is cross-module handoff (collectors/aggregator -> summary input payload), not single-function logic. It does not require real OS/network/subprocess if source clients are replaced with in-process fakes. It does not depend on real model judgment, only that all source fields are present in the payload.","test_description":"Wire real collection/orchestration modules with fake metrics/issue-tracker/deployment clients that return distinct sentinel values; execute report build; assert the exact payload sent to summary-generation contains all three source sections and expected mapped keys/values.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.12,"Integration":0.78,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When one data source is unavailable, the report is produced with a `data unavailable` note for that section rather than aborting.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is resilience/orchestration across modules: one collector fails, pipeline continues, section fallback state propagates into report output. In-process fakes can reproduce unavailable-source errors; no real network/OS behavior is required. Higher levels rejected: System is disqualified because behavior text does not require real transport failure mechanics, only unavailable-source handling; Agentic is disqualified because correctness is fallback control flow, not model output quality.","test_description":"Run pipeline with two fake sources succeeding and one fake source raising an availability error; assert process completes, report contains `data unavailable` in the failed section, and other sections still contain real data.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.09,"Integ